body_text.text:
Additional chronic non-communicable disease was associated with an increase in the number of outpatient visits and inpatient hospital days (table 2
). Overall, the associations between the presence of additional non-communicable diseases and health service use were similar across socioeconomic groups—ie, for each socioeconomic group, those with an additional non-communicable disease had greater health service use (Figure 2, Figure 3). Moreover, differences between socioeconomic groups in the association between physical multimorbidity and outpatient visits were similar across health insurance schemes (figure 2
). A similar pattern was seen for the number of days spent in hospital as an inpatient (figure 3
).
